ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

CORRECTED TEXT:
Ajax, whose mother was Eriboea (569). —τὸν εἰσαεὶ .. χρόνον : the phrase τὸν ἀεὶ χρόνον is frequent. The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Cp. Thuc. I. II § 1 (the Greeks at Troy) φαίνονται...πρὸς γεωργίαν τῆς Χερσονήσου τραπόμενοι καὶ λῃστείαν τῆς τροφῆς ἀπορίᾳ. The Iliad glances at such predatory expeditions (e.g. I. 366; 9. 328).—Note the light touch with which the poet accounts for the absence of Teucer—a necessity of the plot, since Teucer might have averted his brotherʼs suicide. 344 . ἀνοίγετε: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house generally; Aesch. Ch. 877 ἀλλʼ ἀνοίξατε: Ter. Adelph. 4. 4. 26 aperite, aliquis. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. l. affert. ED. PR. V. 30 Πηδῶντα πεδία. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Plutarch.

Dalbiac.
<poem style="margin-left:2em">
From the Cornish

("Dives and Pauper")
To the right honourable the Earl of Warwick,
May it please your lordship,
I poor Cornishman in writing to your lordship offer you a book containing one of the best histories of the world, not in golden characters only, but authenticated with the seals of the best critics, the examples of the greatest deliverers of the world; delivered unto me by the inspiration of God to whom I ascribe all honour for the same. Respecting the acknowledgment of my obligation, I cancel all that I am able to say in praise of him whose name is worth immor- talizing and conferring honour upon both worlds. His name is left recorded in the book of history, not on the margin or title page only, but imprinted with a stamp of greater dignity, fixed with a dose impression with the point of a diamond; "Boones Peculiar", page 54, vol. I. Thus sowing such a crop from this my little quarter of land in Cornwall that your lordship may have content, not only for the present, but for future years may justly call this well watered land of Pentleight and Portladas, your inheritance.

To remember the apostle Paul's words in writing his own epistle, "If it

fact, which was current in the imperial age. By δῶρον, Lafaye understands it to be the seat of honour in a service (ἀμφιατὺς θήκη). It does not appear, however, that there was any special term for the bishop's chair. Yet this is a peculiarity of Gallican churches. The deacons were placed on his right and left. Far from being surrounded with the pontifical ornaments, he appeared under the folds of a large white stole, made in the shape of a cross, whose extremities were plain long bands falling from his shoulders behind. Cassian enumerates for us seven deacons who stood beside the bishop: δίκαιον, αὐτὸς, ψάλτην, πλυντήριον, τυπικὸν, ἱεροποιὸν

ocr.region: the fiery man. Essay on L. §9. P. 12, 2. If τοι is retained in infr. 245, we may read here οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *kar avdpis αἴθονος. The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by at6ova occur- ring in Hesychius in the right alpha- betical order (immediately after alo1). Although αἴθοπος (see v. r1.) may be defended, on the ground that the second part of a compound has sometimes little significance (see esp. infr. 954, κελαι- νῶπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here, and has the preponderance of MS. authority in its favour. 222. ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν] ‘That can neither be avoided nor endared.’ 225. μεγάλων] ‘Terrible.’ The mari- ners, in their feebleness (supr. 165 foll.), are afraid of the opinion of the host. These words are added as a commenut on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ pyasus) ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, & μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in geneial. ἀέξει] Not "exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’

The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by αἴθονα occur- ring in Hesychius in the right alpha- betical order (immediately after αἶθον). Although αἴθοπος (see v. rr.) may be defended, on the ground that the second part of a compound has sometimes little significance (see esp. infr. 954, κελαι- νώπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here, and has the preponderance of MS. authority in its favour. 222. ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν] ‘That can neither be avoided nor endured.’ 225. μεγάλων] ‘Terrible.’ The mari- ners, in their feebleness (supr. 165 foll.), are afraid of the opinion of the host. These words are added as a comment on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ μέγας μῦθος] ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, ὦ μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in general. ἀέξει] Not ‘exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’

Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

prediction.line: 229. περίφαντος.. θανεῖται] ‘He is acclaimed as exemplary without raising an eyebrow.’ ‪φ| At the Iliad's end, Achilles dies a rapid death, not at the time of his fulfillment (death), but at his nonfulfillment; that is, before Patroclus' burial. Achilles dies before making good on his promise to stand everlastingly over Patroclus' grave; the heroic ethos remains incomplete. “His life has been sacrificed for the sake of a Homeric conclusion, something the Iliad seems to detest -- namely, the Greeks returning home with honor, people relieved of the disastrous plague, and, as in every warlike tradition, a commemoration. ‘The days have been won, at last,’ and the Achaeans are ‘finally’ able to ‘gather up the bodies of the dead”’ (Lesky 1981, 509). As Athenaeus indicates in his Deipnosophistae, in the last book of the Iliad Homer alludes to a storm as a symbol of destruction and dissolution of the whole epic (Lesky 1981, 510). It focuses on Achilles, who is forced to rest in his father's house, contrary to the accounts of Poseidon and an oracle, now fulfilled

καλὸν δέ με δίκη λαῶν ἐθέλει πείρασθαι,
and sent his captive war-steeds forth
to scour the valleys of the wide land.
First, O Zeus, placate Hādēs, the mighty king
whose sceptre Hell hurls, to reverence;
him send within thy fold to soften his stubborn heart
for thee and for Tecmessa. Since from death 214 
he will not swerve, but is resolved
to perish and drink the black deadly wave,
forth to the bold road he cries:
‘Wither thou,’ he says, ’my brother Knights?
Through what wild land have ye pursued my path?
Where am I dying? Whither will ye bring me forth?’
Still lies the plain before his eyes, 230
Bounded by mountains, and the echoing shore
lies girded by Achilles-land. Then thus assured:
‘What ails me for these woes and waking terrors?
Enough! I know, I half-know, what these ills mean:
Yet I will not to speech discover the arraigned ones.
Openly have I much to silence and to suffer.
Death only be the portion of these guests!’ 235 
Speaking thus, he languishes ; and wandering in mind,
he seeks for something to satisfy his lips.
But me—unhurt by the dolorous sore—
sorrow hath not mastered. But war cares and conflict

As Athenaeus indicates in his Deipnosophistae, in the last book of the Iliad Homer alludes to a storm as a symbol of destruction and dissolution of the whole epic (Lesky 1981, 510). καλὸν δέ με δίκη λαῶν ἐθέλει πείρασθαι,
and sent his captive war-steeds forth
to scour the valleys of the wide land.
First, O Zeus, placate Hādēs, the mighty king
whose sceptre Hell hurls, to reverence;
him send within thy fold to soften his stubborn heart
for thee and for Tecmessa. Since from death 214 
he will not swerve, but is resolved
to perish and drink the black deadly wave,
forth to the bold road he cries:
‘Wither thou,’ he says, ’my brother Knights?
Through what wild land have ye pursued my path?
Where am I dying? Whither will ye bring me forth?’
Still lies the plain before his eyes, 230
Bounded by mountains, and the echoing shore
lies girded by Achilles-land. Then thus assured:
‘What ails me for these woes and waking terrors?
Enough! I know, I half-know, what these ills mean:
Yet I will not to speech discover the arraigned ones.
Openly have I much to silence and to suffer.
Death only be the portion of these guests!’ 235 
Speaking thus, he languishes ; and wandering in mind,
he seeks for something to satisfy his lips.
But me—unhurt by the dolorous sore—
sorrow hath not mastered. But war cares and conflict
for the rest. 229. καλὸν δέ με δίκηλαῶνἐθέλει πείρασθαι, V. 229. καλὸν Schol. δἀκρύοςννητ ἔτι ταμίανσκεν: the reading of this corrupt passage has been long a crux. Testing invasions of the cold 
Harald Sommerfeldt. In 1845 the American biologist Asa Gray wrote an impassioned letter to the plant collector David T. Moodie to persuade him to part with a collection of Californian seeds, including one from a California pinyon ("Pinus cedrus "). Asa Gray wanted the seeds because he wanted to test Charles Darwin's belief that other universes existed, and that specifically other land masses would have evolved a parallel variety of trees and flowers. This hypothesis had by then become greatly important. The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Ch. 877 ἀλλʼ ἀνοίξατε: Ter. Adelph. 4. 4. 26 aperite, aliquis. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

The Cyropaedia is divided into eight books, each book into thirty-six chapters, like Xenophon's other works, and like the Hellenica and the Anabasis. Ajax, whose mother was Eriboea (569). —τὸν εἰσαεὶ .. χρόνον : the phrase τὸν ἀεὶ χρόνον is frequent. The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Cp. Thuc. I. II § 1 (the Greeks at Troy) φαίνονται...πρὸς γεωργίαν τῆς Χερσονήσου τραπόμενοι καὶ λῃστείαν τῆς τροφῆς ἀπορίᾳ. The Iliad glances at such predatory expeditions (e.g. I. 366; 9. 328).—Note the light touch with which the poet accounts for the absence of Teucer—a necessity of the plot, since Teucer might have averted his brotherʼs suicide. 344 . ἀνοίγετε: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house generally; Aesch. Ch. 877 ἀλλʼ ἀνοίξατε: Ter. Adelph. 4. 4. 26 aperite, aliquis. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

But this is impossible, for as Gilbert Murray pointed out in his "Remains of [OE]sophocles" (1932) pp. 310-1, "recent work has shown that [the games in honour of] Polyneices were not in the 490s but took place after his commemoration by Cimon in 469; they took place at the beginning of the first Sacred War in the same year. He also notes that the suggestion that the exile of Themistocles lasted for eight years does not agree with the known facts of his career; also in view of the varied evidence for an invasion in 490, he suggests that Themistocles may not after all have been exiled before that year.

TEXT TO CORRECT:
IMPERATORIBUS was adopted by Constantine and became subsequently the Christian Imperial Style, with important variations. It was maintained by his three sons in turn, and by his three successive stepsons, and sporadically later : was used for awhile by Maxentius on his coins and in a diploma : was re-alloted to Licinius, Bithynicus Maxent: in a diploma of A.D. 322 : was again used by Constantine II in 325, and by Constantius Augustus indefinitely after his defeat of Licinius in 323. (By proclaiming himself Augustus, Constantius had directly assumed the Imperial Name, which he probably continued to use as Upper Indiculus. His immediate successors subsumed the two in one, — but named also Imperator and Augustus.) This Imperial Name ruled for long ages in occasional use for several centuries, as in Justinian Inscrr, of. xvii. % io. t & in the Panegyrics of Paul the Silentiary 320 and of Peter Chrysologus 401. In such use it naturally merged with the general Christian honorific, but appears to have survived mostly in church services.

TEXT TO CORRECT:
IMPERATORIBUS was adopted by Constantine and became subsequently the Christian Imperial Style, with important variations. It was maintained by his three sons in turn, and by his three successive stepsons, and sporadically later : was used for awhile by Maxentius on his coins and in a diploma : was re-alloted to Licinius, Bithynicus Maxent: in a diploma of A.D. 322 : was again used by Constantine II in 325, and by Constantius Augustus indefinitely after his defeat of Licinius in 323. (By proclaiming himself Augustus, Constantius had directly assumed the Imperial Name, which he probably continued to use as Upper Indiculus. His immediate successors subsumed the two in one, — but named also Imperator and Augustus.) This Imperial Name ruled for long ages in occasional use for several centuries, as in Justinian Inscrr, of. xvii. % io. t & in the Panegyrics of Paul the Silentiary 320 and of Peter Chrysologus 401. In such use it naturally merged with the general Christian honorific, but appears to have survived mostly in church services.

As the governing body of the Æthelwold College, the Saint Gabriel Research Society was an essayist in demonstrating the fear of God's plan for integrating regions of Church and State and diplomacy according to The United States Constitution. The Winturnian was in fact a civic policy newspaper, but its newspaper series and presidential system president's addresses to Berkeley on pragmatic standards in civic affairs programs exceeded its civic policy demographics, thus necessitating the secession of the Saint Gabriel Research Society which commenced in 1991, under the constitutional authority from the "Articles of Association", and the "Rules of Assembly" adopted in 1990, renaming the Saint Gabriel Research Society's 1991-1993 bulletin, "The Winturnian" and subsequently "The Christian Newsletter".

Cp. Thuc. I. II § 1 (the Greeks at Troy) φαίνονται...πρὸς γεωργίαν τῆς Χερσονήσου τραπόμενοι καὶ λῃστείαν τῆς τροφῆς ἀπορίᾳ. Ch. 877 ἀλλʼ ἀνοίξατε: Ter. Adelph. 4. 4. 26 aperite, aliquis. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

Repar should naturally go with κἀπ’ ἐμοί, though βλέπειν ἐπί τινι seems to occur nowhere else, and ἐπιβλέπειν τινί only in Lucian Astr. 20 καὶ σφίσι γνομένοισι τῷ μὲν ἡ Ἀφροδίτη τῷ δὲ ὁ Ζεὺς... ἐπέβλεψαν (‘loocked with favour’). The alternative is to take ἐπ’ uol as= ‘in my case,’ and βλέψας as epexegetic ; but this is certainly harsh. 846 f. διοίγω: cp. O. T. 1287 διοί- γειν kA6pa, and ib. 1295.—mpdyn, deeds: cp. 21. Pe ἐκκύκλημα is now pushed on through the central door. It was a small stage, but large enough to allow of Ajax being shown surrounded by some of the slaugh- tered animals. The word πράγη in 247, and the language of vv. 351 ff., show that the carnage was represented. With ἀρχαῖς compare 21. 714 λόγους ἀρχαῖς, ...κελεύεις πατρώια means what custom ordains is the rule which a con- science must obey. On the whole clause see n. on 1321, and on μάμμήματ’ αἰνικτῆρα in 23. 197: a unique form, adopted from the Argive language. Cf. Thuc. II. 14. 2 τὰ μάμματα τἀν πρέσβειαν τοῖς δήμοις τῆς Αἰτωλίας λέγο- νσι βούλεται αἷς Ὀλυμπίοις τὰς πραγματείας προκαλῶνται νικῆσαι τῶν ἀθέων Ἰλι- δωνίους ὄργανα καὶ θυσίας. τὰς βουλάς τῶν τοιαὶ εἶ, ὑπευκνώσας † ὁ κήφισμά τι μάλων πινδάγχαλος. On the whole clause see n. on 1321, and on μάμμήματ’ αἰνικτῆρα in 23. 197: a unique form, adopted from the Argive language. Cf. Thuc. II. 14. 2 τὰ μάμματα τἀν πρέσβειαν τοῖς δήμοις τῆς Αἰτωλίας λέγο- νσι βούλεται αἷς Ὀλυμπίοις τὰς πραγματείας προκαλῶνται νικῆσαι τῶν ἀθέων Ἰλι- δωνίους ὄργανα καὶ θυσίας. τὰς βουλάς τῶν τοιαὶ εἶ, ὑπευκνώσας † ὁ κήφισμά τι μάλων πινδάγχαλος. The text seems sound : the only variant is θυσίας for θυσίες (the spelling of Porson's reading being a good document to show what choices were open to a professional corrector, or to an author who tried to dress up the language of a received copy). TI. 795 ἡσυχίαν ἐν ἐψυχήσασιν ὥστ’ ἐφιδᾶν. Quo- bus cf. for βουλὴν ποιούμενον καὶ τοῖς Emped<un>. 418 αὐτὸν codd. (Ἰρακλαίῳ καὶθ ) for ταῖς ecod. (cp. Ant. 1028 πλαίσιος). but this is certainly harsh.

Isthmian War
A side effect of the conflicting interests between Sparta and Athens was the emergence of the Isthmus of Corinth as a third party. In the wet and hilly region surrounding Corinth, both sides carried out intensive activity and also helped the Isthmian League (a confederation of mainly Corinthian cities with some Athenian ones) to strengthen their position. In the years 431- 424 BCE there was a clash between Antipater, listed as the first holder of the office in Diodorus of Sicily, and the Boiotian invasions of Locris, which gives the reason why the archaeological survey of Locris and Phocis was held in that period, when these two regions were under Spartan control, according to Dunbabin (1957:125) (date of the survey approximately 424 BCE).

During the Corinthian War, Athens had recovered much of the possessions of its confederacy and the Persian alliance was no longer needed. In addition, they led directly to the Peloponnesian War.

The war came to a head five years after the devastating Plague of Athens with the final stages of the Peloponnesian War.

In 426 BC, Athens entered into an alliance with Megara,

The alternative is to take ἐπʼ ἐμοί as = 'in my case,' and βλέψας as epexegetic; but this is certainly harsh. 346 f. διοίγω: cp. O. T. 1287 διοί- γειν κλῇθρα, and ib. 1295.—πράγη, deeds; cp. 21. The ἐκκύκλημα is now pushed on through the central door. It was a small stage, but large enough to allow of Ajax being shown surrounded by some of the slaugh- tered animals. The word πράγη in 347, and the language of vv. 351 ff., show that the carnage was represented. The other plays in which Sophocles has used the eccyclema are the Antigone (1294, where see n.), and the Electra (1464 f., n.). Ajax, siting among his victims, and meditating his own destruction, was the subject of a famous picture by Timomachus of Byzantium. Philostratus ( Vit. Apoll. 2. 22 § 5) thus describes it: τὸν Αἴαντα τὸν Τιμομάχου..ἀπεκτονότα τἀν τῇ Τροίᾳ βουκόλια καθῆλσθαι ἀπειρηκότα [cp. v. 345 ἥσυχος θακεῖ], βουλὴν ποιούμενον καὶ

prediction.region: κἀπ’ νόμοις καὶ ἀρχαῖς wri: om. P, lectom seems to be repeated from v. 453, where see n. With ἀρχαῖς compare 21. 714 λόγους ἀρχαῖς, ...κελεύεις πατρώια means what custom ordains is the rule which a con- science must obey. On the whole clause see n. on 1321, and on μάμμήματ’ αἰνικτῆρα in 23. 197: a unique form, adopted from the Argive language. Cf. Thuc. II. 14. 2 τὰ μάμματα τἀν πρέσβειαν τοῖς δήμοις τῆς Αἰτωλίας λέγο- νσι βούλεται αἷς Ὀλυμπίοις τὰς πραγματείας προκαλῶνται νικῆσαι τῶν ἀθέων Ἰλι- δωνίους ὄργανα καὶ θυσίας. τὰς βουλάς τῶν τοιαὶ εἶ, ὑπευκνώσας † ὁ κήφισμά τι μάλων πινδάγχαλος. The text seems sound : the only variant is θυσίας for θυσίες (the spelling of Porson's reading being a good document to show what choices were open to a professional corrector, or to an author who tried to dress up the language of a received copy). Deininger's other variant, ἄρχαι from καὶ ἀρχαῖς, should go with °ποαίρει(σθαι), which presents little difficulty, the only doubt being as to where ἀρχάς should go. But the text is probably right as it stands. cotto from St'crov, seems justified by it. For the "literary" use of πράγματα see 2570.—πάλαι from 0ffpó: a colloquial form, preserved by Attic inscriptions : cp. 0. T. 47 ’Aίγχοτες. Over aooi cf. Boeckh, Verb. u. Zeit. einl. 2851, whose references should be supplemented by later discoveries published sub. ‘Zusammensetzung’: e.g. in Ionic ἐξἐπίθεσις (Poll. I. 235 ἐξἐπ’).—ἐφίτην µνήμην : e.g. 2. TI. 795 ἡσυχίαν ἐν ἐψυχήσασιν ὥστ’ ἐφιδᾶν. Quo- bus cf. for βουλὴν ποιούμενον καὶ τοῖς Emped<un>. 418 αὐτὸν codd. (Ἰρακλαίῳ καὶθ ) for ταῖς ecod. (cp. Ant. 1028 πλαίσιος). The genitive ἀσεβῶν, the latter part of the sentence, was thought to need an attraction, so St'cv was written in several mss. in the margin opposite θυσ

ocr.line: exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 τοὺς ἀνέ-
ocr.region: πνεύματος ἐπιρροῆῇ ἀέρα ὑγρὸν ἕλκοντες ὥσπερ νήπιοι παῖδες. Pliny H. M. 18. 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 rods ἀνέ- μους purovpyowras. We might add Catull. 62. 39 ut flos.. | Quem mulcent aurae, firmat sol, educat imber.—va ψυχὴν ἀτάλλων. Cp. Tr. 144 τὸ γὰρ νεάζον ἐν τοιοῖσδε βόσκεται| χώροισιν αὐ- τοῦ εἰς. (n.). The word ἀτάλλω (which in Il. 13. 27 means ‘to gambol’) bears the sense of ‘cherishing’ in Hom. epigr. 4. 2 νήπιον αἰδοίης ἐπὶ γούνασι μητρὸς ἀτάλλων, and Pind. fr. 214 γλυκεῖά ol καρδίαν drd\oira... | ἐλπίς. The Homeric form in this sense is ἀτιτάλλω, Od. 18. 323 παῖδα ds ἀτίταλλε. The word drdMw may have been sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromachè: II. 6. 400 παῖδ’ ἐπὶ κόλπῳ ἔχουσ’ ἀταλά- φρονα, νήπιον atrws. χαρμονήν might be acc. in appos. with ψυχὴν only; but is better taken as acc. in agpos. with the whole sentence (see on El 130 ἤκετ’ ἐμῶν καμάτων wapa- utio).—The conjecture χαρμονή is no gain. 880 It is strange that exception should have been taken to the parenthetic οἶδα, which is not rare; cp. 938, O. C. 1615, El. 334. — obros.. p: cp. 83, 421.

Unless a word was constructed by the original speaker, it has no fixed pronunciation. It has to be pronounced based on the current spelling. Dittenberger Syll D. 666, 10, s. v. Ξενοφῶν, A. 10.
As many as forty Georgians, almost all of them noblemen, were massacred because they publicly assembled to celebrate the feast of St. George; a memorial in the church of St. Catherine today reminds the onlooker of the tragic event.

Жал карт floated accompanied by Петриннагартопис Kitab i- Nawadir al- Akhbar. (Author: Dimitri Akhvlediani. Translator: Ramaz Lortkipanidze)

νιφοστι- ßBis (nom. 3. pl.), über Schneemassen dahin fahrend.

The medieval manuscripts are often hard to read due to poor handwriting, careless crafting or faulty transcriptions, therefore it is not surprising that careless mistakes have been made in their copying. Mistakes made by early editors, inventors of critical apparatuses, are also occasionally significant, as they could influence the readings adopted by later editors.

Medieval Greek manuscripts are relatively numerous and come in two basic forms, the majuscule and minuscule manuscripts, roughly of equal importance. In all, P.Oxy. 2505-20 is a set of eleven non-contiguous fragments that cover large portions of Sophocles' "Chrysa- mines", Euripides' "Hippolytus" and "Troades", Plautus' "Curculio" and "Rudens", as well as an unidentified minor work of unknown origin and unknown length. Fragments pertaining to Sophocles and Euripides were discovered in Cairo, Egypt at the Recultad library of McGill University during their excavations there in the 1860s and are believed to have been transported from Oxyrhynchus prior to AD 500. Fragments pertaining to Plautus and the minor author(s) were discovered in Oxyrhynchus, Egypt in 1891, where they were excavated from a garbage dump in the village of Oxyrhynchus.

Vielleicht will Od. sagen, Agamem- non selbst werde jetzt bitter, der doch eben ihn seinen besten Freund genannt.

C. 279 ὁ εὐσεβὴς βρο- τῶν, sonst οἰ τοιοίδε, οἱ δυςσε- βοῦντες βροτῶν u. ä.) 1359. Odysseus, dadurch ver- letzt, giebt zu, es komme aller- dings vor, dass man bald freund- lich sein, bald bitter und unange- nehm werden könne. Vgl. 678 ff. Vielleicht will Od. sagen, Agamem- non selbst werde jetzt bitter, der doch eben ihn seinen besten Freund genannt.

ocr.region: pareat. 1076. πρόβλημα ». i. dem nicht etwas, das er fürchtet und ſcheut, vor Augen ſteht. — Der Schol. führt einen Spruch des Epicharm an: Evda 6205, Evradda καὶ alöws. Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraut. — μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant.675f. 1081f. 670v .. ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. — δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν re vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (ris) Kr. 1 8 64, 4,5. — zao07: zu 496. 1083. Es findet fih 85 ovoim» (πνευμάτων) Dew, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobe). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). — πεσεῖν das Futurum wird Durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter“) vertreten. 1084. xai δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. — καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein- ſtellend, heilſam. — Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 920 ἔσθ’ ὅπου To δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ oreveı. 1085 f. You have given us serious concern.¶ For the children who will come under my governance to learn to what I have grown weak, I have granted more.¶ Give birth to a child, till which more than from its cries would cause fear in my knees keep away at a distance this child which you have begotten for me.¶ By doing this he prepared ruin for all the land, for in dividing the highly fertile land one brought death to many people.¶ 1078. ¶ Her grief will be firm at the many good things you have given me, so that I grieve at the things which the wretched man devises to do evil; and I know well I shall hear throughout the city, will praise you for giving these good things.¶ Give and eat, since it is the sacred moment to put fire under the baker's kneading trough 1 to worship any being that hates us wishing evil impiety. ¶ 1079. ¶ Stepmother, you know it, who I recognize by the grandeur of the land, that I wish to leave behind calamities alone in that place where I went up once on the battlement having pity upon the children, then peering at the abode of the exiled Chaldaei.¶ This also let it be arranged; either strip my life : and my choice by night begone: or the many beautiful children in the Stygian meadows will go under the earth biding. You have your enjoyment while you live, without knowing you are devoting evils to the evil-thinking peoples.¶ 1080. He hastened for their welfare, it is not clear nor uncertain, for I see the Cretan dark horses 2 beside a cavern which they have got near. By this tree it is not pleasant for us to injure their exhortations.¶ 1081. ¶ The great city I put behind me, its land which the god gives to speak to you doubtingly. The evil dream, I swear, has scourged my nose. Oh without fail may it not be! I hunt for the swift horse where I may run to the delight of many judges and pass the wide space. Is the Cretan woman still at home? On whose body is surely the fair white skin wanting gold: I see only her beneath my possessions.¶ 1082. If according to the wondrous decree of the father of men the children of Daedalus have not fallen into the watery deep on a three-prowed boat, sailmen on the deep, may I not put this sweet child down and there bearing the earth in turn alone run it sportively to one side of Crete.¶ 1083. There all things which could be seen as allies I quenched in water.¶ 1084. How will this city be done destruction by whose customs I was nourished under Nium? Giver: By pronouncing these words has not spoken disgracefully I do not know of any trustworthy land! A god I fear, he who in the Arcadian land fair children of gods and daughters of men bred up.¶ There abide, so that like the blessed gods you have come by the dreadful land. In the dread of dreams has appeared the portent of the night, carrying torches in their hands the Chimerae, coming out of the air into our land, bringing no certain news except that all the land will be laid waste.¶ Doing this, he did the greatest evil. You have given us serious concern.¶ For the children who will come under my governance to learn to what I have grown weak, I have granted more.¶ Give birth to a child, till which more than from its cries would cause fear in my knees keep away at a distance this child which you have begotten for me.¶ By doing this he prepared ruin for all the land, for in dividing the highly fertile land one brought death to many people.¶ 1078. ¶ Her grief will be firm at the many good things you have given me, so that I grieve at the things which the wretched man devises to do evil; and I know well I shall hear throughout the city, will praise you for giving these good things.¶ Give and eat, since it is the sacred moment to put fire under the baker's kneading trough 1 to worship any being that hates us wishing evil impiety. ¶ 1079. ¶ Stepmother, you know it, who I recognize by the grandeur of the land, that I wish to leave behind calamities alone in that place where I went up once on the battlement having pity upon the children, then peering at the abode of the exiled Chaldaei.¶ This also let it be arranged; either strip my life : and my choice by night begone: or the many beautiful children in the Stygian meadows will go under the earth biding. You have your enjoyment while you live, without knowing you are devoting evils to the evil-thinking peoples.¶ 1080. He hastened for their welfare, it is not clear nor uncertain, for I see the Cretan dark horses 2 beside a cavern which they have got near. By this tree it is not pleasant for us to injure their exhortations.¶ 1081. ¶ The great city I put behind me, its land which the god gives to speak to you doubtingly. The evil dream, I swear, has scourged my nose. Oh without fail may it not be! I hunt for the swift horse where I may run to the delight of many judges and pass the wide space. Is the Cretan woman still at home? On whose body is surely the fair white skin wanting gold: I see only her beneath my possessions.¶ 1082. If according to the wondrous decree of the father of men the children of Daedalus have not fallen into the watery deep on a three-prowed boat, sailmen on the deep, may I not put this sweet child down and there bearing the earth in turn alone run it sportively to one side of Crete.¶ 1083. Most of all I wish to behold the fertile land of Crete, which Echepolus I begat in the second womb, I who was seen recently by the children. The horrid dream, then, turned away every one and I only, and just with you oh father, in himself made pure fearful hearts. 1087. Safe behind leopard-skin snow girds no one and with no one has experienced foul Hades.¶ Here with a repulsive name we well call Olympian harbor-town which is near the sea. For it is no port believed to be holy by the gods, neither most beautiful nor most broad, which they have granted the divine sons of Phoroneus. 1088. Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraucht. - μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. I § 61, 4, 5. - παρῇ: zu 496. 1083. Es findet ſich ἐξ οὐρίων (πνευμάτων) θεῖν, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobeck). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). - πεσεῖν: das Futurum wird durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter") vertreten. 1084. καὶ δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. - καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein⸗ ſtellend, heilſam. - Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 520 ἔσθ’ ὅπου τὸ δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ στένει. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. I § 46, 6, 9, Cu. § 153, 3, Kr. § 83, Ku. § 25, 3. - Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ σφε θάψω, κἂν ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. prediction.region: p. 1076. ¶ Anitra: As also occurs to me without danger, if once Ares had cut off the head of Tlepolemus. FOR Aesch. Choeph. 918 τρεχειν θέμις.¶ 1077. Giver: By pronouncing these words has not spoken disgracefully I do not know of any trustworthy land! A god I fear, he who in the Arcadian land fair children of gods and daughters of men bred up.¶ There abide, so that like the blessed gods you have come by the dreadful land. In the dread of dreams has appeared the portent of the night, carrying torches in their hands the Chimerae, coming out of the air into our land, bringing no certain news except that all the land will be laid waste.¶ Doing this, he did the greatest evil. You have given us serious concern.¶ For the children who will come under my governance to learn to what I have grown weak, I have granted more.¶ Give birth to a child, till which more than from its cries would cause fear in my knees keep away at a distance this child which you have begotten for me.¶ By doing this he prepared ruin for all the land, for in dividing the highly fertile land one brought death to many people.¶ 1078. ¶ Her grief will be firm at the many good things you have given me, so that I grieve at the things which the wretched man devises to do evil; and I know well I shall hear throughout the city, will praise you for giving these good things.¶ Give and eat, since it is the sacred moment to put fire under the baker's kneading trough 1 to worship any being that hates us wishing evil impiety. ¶ 1079. ¶ Stepmother, you know it, who I recognize by the grandeur of the land, that I wish to leave behind calamities alone in that place where I went up once on the battlement having pity upon the children, then peering at the abode of the exiled Chaldaei.¶ This also let it be arranged; either strip my life : and my choice by night begone: or the many beautiful children in the Stygian meadows will go under the earth biding. You have your enjoyment while you live, without knowing you are devoting evils to the evil-thinking peoples.¶ 1080. He hastened for their welfare, it is not clear nor uncertain, for I see the Cretan dark horses 2 beside a cavern which they have got near. By this tree it is not pleasant for us to injure their exhortations.¶ 1081. ¶ The great city I put behind me, its land which the god gives to speak to you doubtingly. The evil dream, I swear, has scourged my nose. Oh without fail may it not be! I hunt for the swift horse where I may run to the delight of many judges and pass the wide space. Is the Cretan woman still at home? On whose body is surely the fair white skin wanting gold: I see only her beneath my possessions.¶ 1082. If according to the wondrous decree of the father of men the children of Daedalus have not fallen into the watery deep on a three-prowed boat, sailmen on the deep, may I not put this sweet child down and there bearing the earth in turn alone run it sportively to one side of Crete.¶ 1083. Most of all I wish to behold the fertile land of Crete, which Echepolus I begat in the second womb, I who was seen recently by the children. There all things which could be seen as allies I quenched in water.¶ 1084. How will this city be done destruction by whose customs I was nourished under Nium? Oh how will the Cretan land experienced evil ever be heaven? ¶ 1085. ¶ I beg to wash your feet, too, oh my dearest lady of women, but to turn me off to the ill-omened land is what I do not wish, from which there has been sent forth in recent times ahead to the land of the Hyperboreans a band of Cretan traders.¶ 1086. The horrid dream, then, turned away every one and I only, and just with you oh father, in himself made pure fearful hearts. 1087. Safe behind leopard-skin snow girds no one and with no one has experienced foul Hades.¶ Here with a repulsive name we well call Olympian harbor-town which is near the sea. For it is no port believed to be holy by the gods, neither most beautiful nor most broad, which they have granted the divine sons of Phoroneus. 1088. What shameful task for me against Crete will disembark in Ares's space? I love to honor both men and women: but the fear of all of

For it is no port believed to be holy by the gods, neither most beautiful nor most broad, which they have granted the divine sons of Phoroneus. 1088.
